| 3 | LLL | R | 12.407 ns |

---

## Success Criteria

A valid result requires:

1. Statistically significant difference  
2. Reproducibility  
3. Survival under all control tests  

---

## Null Result Interpretation

If no difference is observed:

> The results support standard quantum mechanics:  
> no measurable influence from prior path history beyond the current state.

---

## Positive Result Interpretation

If differences are observed:

Possible implications:

- Residual path-history dependence  
- Non-Markovian behaviour  
- Incomplete state description  
- Experimental artifact (must be ruled out)

---

## Summary

| Test | Standard Prediction | Confidence Bias Prediction |
|------|------------------|--------------------------|
| Probability | No difference | Small ε shift |
| Timing | No difference | Small Δt shift |
| History effect | None | Weak residual influence |

---

## Final Question

> After repeated forced preparation into a state, does the particle behave identically when symmetry is restored, or does prior history leave a measurable trace in probability or timing?

